               <bibl><ptr target="roberthell1"/></bibl>, whence <bibl><ptr target="robertBE"/> <citedRange>1941.179</citedRange></bibl>;
               <bibl><ptr target="roberthelliii"/> <citedRange>140</citedRange> f. and pl. IX</bibl>.
            </p>
         </div>

         

         <div type="edition" xml:lang="grc" xml:space="preserve">
            <div subtype="section" n="a" type="textpart">
               <ab>
                  <lb n="1"/><persName type="attested"><name nymRef="Ἑρμῆς">Ἑρμῆς</name></persName>
               </ab>
            </div>
            <div subtype="section" n="b" type="textpart">
               <ab> 
                   <lb n="1"/><persName type="attested"><name nymRef="Ἑρμῆς">Ἑρμῆς</name> <w lemma="ὁ">ὁ</w>
                   <w lemma="πρίν">πρὶν</w>
                   <lb n="2"/><space quantity="1" unit="character"/> <name nymRef="Φίλων">Φίλων</name></persName> <space quantity="1" unit="character"/> 
               </ab>
            </div>
         </div>
         
         <div type="translation" xml:space="preserve">
            <p>
               <note>a</note> Hermes</p><p>
               <note>b</note> Hermes, who was formerly Philo</p>
         </div>
         
         <div type="commentary">
            <p>Approximately a pair with <ref type="inscription">P31100</ref>. Re-used as the cover of a late tomb.</p>
            <p>The palm branches indicates nine victories. </p>
            <p>On double names for gladiators see Robert, <title>Gladiateurs</title>, p. 297. 
               Neither the original name here nor the “stage-name” (which recurs among gladiators, Robert p. 109) are at all innovative.</p>
         </div>
         
